<DOC><DOCNO> AP881119-0124 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-11-19-88 1727EST</FILEID><FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     11-19 0652</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0668</SECOND><HEAD>Heavy Rain From Texas To W.Va.</HEAD><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   Heavy rain fell Saturday from Texas across the Mississippi Riverinto the Ohio Valley, causing some flooding, and snow fell acrossthe northern Plains and the southern Plains.   Flash flood watches were issued for parts of northeastern Texas,the Missouri Bootheel, western and central Kentucky, westernTennessee, and southwestern into northeastern Arkansas.   Central Arkansas got the heaviest rain, with up to 9 inches atLittle Rock from Friday evening to Saturday afternoon, and 6 inchesfell in parts of central and northeastern Arkansas.   The Saline River at Benton, Ark., just southwest of Little Rock,was 2 feet above flood stage during the morning, a rise of 16 feetin 24 hours. The river was expected to crest at 8 feet above floodstage.   Parts of western Tennessee got 3 to 4 inches of rain during thenight and many small streams and drainage ditches were full oroverflowing. Dyersburg got 2.5 inches.   Western Kentucky got 3 to 5 inches overnight with 2 to 3 inchesover the central part of the state.   In southeastern Missouri, Caruthersville got 5.48 inches of rainovernight, and more than 2 inches fell from West Plains into CapeGirardeau.   Locally heavy rain was reported with thunderstorms fromnortheastern Texas into parts of central Mississippi, and Avery,Texas, got 2.51 inches of rain overnight. Thunderstorms producedafternoon wind gusts to 70 mph near Gilmer, uprooting trees.   Street flooding was reported near Summit, Miss., in Pike County,and 2 to 4 inches of rain was measured during the morning atJackson, Miss.   In the six hours up to 1 p.m. EST, 1.85 inches fell at Memphis,Tenn.; 1.42 inches at Columbus, Miss.; and 1.06 inches atCharleston, W.Va.   Snow fell from east-central New Mexico into northwesternOklahoma, and a mixture of snow and sleet was reported over parts ofcentral Kansas. Two inches of snow accumulated at Gage, Okla., withan inch reported at Albuquerque and Clovis, N.M.   That snow was expected to move farther out onto the Plains and awinter storm warning was posted for the Texas Panhandle, with stormwatches out into parts of Oklahoma, Kansas and Missouri.   Snow also fell across the northern Plains to the Great Lakes,from the eastern Dakotas into Minnesota and parts of Upper Michigan.Duluth, Minn., got 2 inches of snow, for a total of 7 inches on theground.   Elsewhere, rain was scattered into the mid Atlantic states, withsleet icing roads over parts of Maryland.   Showers invaded the northern Pacific Coast region and snow wasexpected in the Cascades of Washington state.   Temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. EST ranged from 10degrees at Fargo, N.D., to 91 at McAllen, Texas. Saturday morning'sofficial low was 6 degrees below zero at Gallup, N.M.   For Sunday, heavy snow was forecast across south-central and muchof eastern Kansas into northern Missouri. Rain was forecast from themiddle Mississippi Valley through the Ohio and Tennessee valleys,the lower Great Lakes and the mid Atlantic region into New England.Showers and thunderstorms, some possibly severe, were forecast fromthe Tennessee Valley into the central Gulf Coast. Widespread showerswere forecast across the Pacific Northwest and along the northernPacific Coast.   Highs in the 20s were predicted over the northern Plains; in the30s from the northern high Plains through the middle and lowerMissouri Valley and central Kansas into the upper Mississippi Valleyand upper Great Lakes; in the 60s across southern California and thedesert Southwest, except 70s for southwestern Arizona and the LosAngeles basin; in the 60s and 70s from southern Texas through thecentral Gulf Coast region, the Tennessee Valley and the centralAppalachians into the mid Atlantic Coast; in the 80s across thesouthern Atlantic Coast and Florida; and in the 40s or 50s acrossmuch of the rest of the nation.</TEXT></DOC>